{"title_page": "Saidi of Tidore", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name  = Saidi\n|succession  = Sultan of Tidore\n|reign       = 1640-1657\n|predecessor = [[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]]\n|successor   = [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Saifuddin]]\n|regnal name = \n|house       = \n|father      = [[Ngarolamo]]\n|mother      = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = 7 January 1657\n|religion    = [[Islam]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Sultan Saidi''' (d. 7 January 1657) was the tenth Sultan of [[Tidore]] in [[Maluku islands]]. He was also known as '''Magiau''' and ruled from 1640 to 1657. His reign saw intermittent hostilities with Tidore's traditional rival, the [[Sultanate of Ternate]], which included interference in an anti-Dutch rebellion in Ternate and [[Ambon]] and attempts to increase Tidorese territory in Maluku.\n\n==Power struggles and succession==\n\nSaidi was a son of Sultan [[Ngarolamo]] who was deposed by his rival [[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]] in 1634. He stayed with his father and 200 loyal retainers in exile on [[Ternate Island]] until 1639, when Ngarolamo was killed because of his secret deliberations with the [[Spanish people|Spanish]], the traditional allies of the Tidore Sultans. This murder was soon followed by another one in August 1639, when Gorontalo was killed by a Spanish officer for treacherous collusion with the Ternatans.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1890) ''Bouwstoffen voor de geschiedenis der Nederlanders in den Maleischen Archipel'', Vol. II. 's Gravenhage: Nijhoff, p. 380-3.</ref> Now Tidore was split between two camps; one favoured Gorontalo's son [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Kaicili Golofino]] while another wanted Saidi. The succession dispute lasted into 1640 but was finally resolved in favour of Saidi, who was the Spanish candidate. Ternate's ally, the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC) preferred to stay out of this dispute.<ref>W.P. Coolhaas, ed. (1964) ''Generale missiven van Gouverneurs-Generaal en Raden aan Heren XVII der Verenigde Oostindische Compagnie'', Deel II. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 105.</ref>\n\n==Uneasy relationship with the Spanish==\n\nAt his accession Saidi had to promise to fulfill a number of points. He should provide military assistance to the Spanish establishments in Maluku when needed, he was only to sell [[cloves]] to the Spaniards, and he must allow anyone who so desired to become a Catholic. According to Spanish opinions he failed in all these commitments. On the contrary he strove to manage the spice trade in Tidore's own interests and forbade his subjects to sell the cloves to Spanish buyers. Saidi also interfered in the affairs of the [[Sangihe Islands]] north of Maluku, vassals under the [[Spanish Philippines]], where he supported a Muslim rebel with soldiers and Islamic preachers against the Christian ruler of Kalongan. He even had the rebel chief consecrated as ruler in the mosque of Tidore and, in the Spanish interpretation, reserved for himself the role of emperor.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1981) \"The 'Discurso politico del gobierno Maluco' of Fr. Francisco Comb\u00e9s and its historical impact\", ''Philippine Studies'' 29, p. 328.</ref> The precarious situation of the Spanish in Maluku nevertheless forced them to maintain the Tidore alliance, since Saidi was their only potential supporter in the region.\n\n==Continuing struggles against Ternate and the VOC==\n\nThe ongoing war between the [[Spanish Empire]] and the [[Dutch Republic]] was matched by hostilities in Maluku where Spain and Tidore stood against the VOC and Ternate.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1984) ''Documenta Malucensia'', Vol. III. Rome: Jesuit Historical Institute, p. 2-6.</ref> The Dutch actively tried to prevent any attempts to make a separate peace between Ternate and Tidore. The VOC noted that Saidi was a political man who was no great friend of Spain but who strove to secure Tidore's position within the power balance between the Europeans.<ref>W.P. Coolhaas, ed. (1964), p. 589.</ref> Several clashed nevertheless took place during the 1640s. Tidore turned out to be the more successful \"due to its greater carefulness and bravery\"<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895) ''Bouwstoffen voor de geschiedenis der Nederlanders in den Maleischen Archipel'', Vol. III. 's Gravenhage: Nijhoff, p. 443.</ref> Foodstuff was brought to Tidore from its vassals in [[Halmahera]] and even from the [[Raja Ampat|Papuan Islands]], where Tidorese influence had been established by this time. One of Saidi's helpers was the chief Gurabesi whom later traditions associate with the origins of Tidore rule in the Papuan lands.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895), p. 444.</ref> In 1649 a number of battles and mutual raids took place, culminating in a Tidore-Spanish invasion in Ternate where the Dutch were defeated with considerable losses. Before the VOC were able to stage a counter-attack, news of the [[Peace of Westphalia]] reached the East Indies, and hostilities were cancelled.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895), p. 444-6.</ref>\n\n==Interference in anti-VOC rebellion==\n\nShortly after this, the VOC-backed Sultan of Ternate, [[Mandar Syah]], was opposed by his brothers and part of the Ternatan elite. The Dutch commander Arnold de Vlamingh van Outshoorn suppressed an attempt to replace Mandar Syah, and the Ternatans had to agree on a treaty in 1652 where they were stipulated to extirpate clove trees in their dominions.<ref>Leonard Andaya (1993) ''The world of Maluku''. Honolulu: Hawai'i University Press, p. 167-8.</ref> This would ensure VOC monopoly on the spice trade, but the treaty was insufficient as long as Tidore sold its cloves to other buyers. Since Saidi actively supported the rebels in Ternate without Spanish approval, De Vlamingh van Outshoorn declared war on Tidore, hoping to eliminate the Tidorese clove production. In order not to antagonize the Spanish, [[Tidore Island]] was not attacked; rather, an expedition under Simon Cos was dispatched to worst Tidore's vassals in Halmahera and the Papuan Islands. The expedition was not particularly successful, and in the meantime the Papuan Raja of [[Salawati]] raided in [[Ambon]] on behalf of Sultan Saidi.<ref>P.J.B.C. Robid\u00e9 van der Aa (1879) ''Reizen naar Nederlandsch Nieuw-Guinea''. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 358.[https://archive.org/details/reizennaarneder00crabgoog/page/n400/mode/2up]</ref> However, the efforts of Saidi to take over the Ternatan parts of Halmahera also failed, and the increasingly irritated Spanish finally arrested the Sultan in 1654 for disturbing the peace. He was however soon set free again, and peace with the VOC followed.<ref>A. Haga (1884) ''Nederlandsch Nieuw Guinea en de Papoesche eilanden. Historische bijdrage, 1500-1883''. Batavia: Bruing, p. 67-8.[https://archive.org/details/nederlandschnie01wetegoog/page/n124/mode/2up]</ref> The Spanish claimed that they saved the skins of the Dutch in Maluku by depriving the rebels in Ternate and Ambon of Tidorese support.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1981), 332-3.</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nSultan Saidi passed away on 7 January 1657, since long suffering from [[leprocy]]. His demise immediately triggered a succession war. He sired two sons called Weda (alias Mole) and Duko, and a daughter who had been betrothed to Mandar Syah in 1651 though the engagement was broken due to the war.<ref>C.F. van Fraassen (1987) ''Ternate, de Molukken en de Indonesische Archipel''. Leiden: Rijksmuseum te Leiden, Vol. II, p. 20.</ref> Weda was proclaimed Sultan on his father's demise. However, the VOC and Ternate brought forward Kaicili Golofino who had stayed in exile in Ternate since 1640. Golofino soon had the upper hand and was enthroned under the name [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Sultan Saifuddin]].<ref>Coolhaas, W.P., ed. (1968) ''Generale missiven van Gouverneurs-Generaal en Raden aan Heren XVII der Verenigde Oostindische Compagnie'', Deel III. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 150.</ref> Under him Tidore finally took the step from a Spanish to a Dutch ally.<ref>Leonard Andaya (1993), p. 170-1.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rulers of Maluku]]\n* [[Spice trade]]\n* [[Tidore Sultanate]]\n* [[Sultanate of Ternate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Sultan of Tidore|years=1640-1657}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Saifuddin of Tidore|Saifuddin]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[Category:People from Maluku Islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name  = Saidi\n|succession  = Sultan of Tidore\n|reign       = 1640-1657\n|predecessor = [[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]]\n|successor   = [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Saifuddin]]\n|regnal name = \n|house       = \n|father      = [[Ngarolamo]]\n|mother      = \n|birth_date  = \n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = 7 January 1657\n|religion    = [[Islam]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Sultan Saidi''' (d. 7 January 1657) was the tenth Sultan of [[Tidire Sultanate|Tidore]] in [[Maluku islands]]. He was also known as '''Magiau''' and ruled from 1640 to 1657. His reign saw intermittent hostilities with Tidore's traditional rival, the [[Sultanate of Ternate]], which included interference in an anti-Dutch rebellion in Ternate and [[Ambon]] and attempts to increase Tidorese territory in Maluku.\n\n==Power struggles and succession==\n\nSaidi was a son of Sultan [[Ngarolamo]] who was deposed by his rival [[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]] in 1634. He stayed with his father and 200 loyal retainers in exile on [[Ternate Island]] until 1639, when Ngarolamo was killed because of his secret deliberations with the [[Spanish people|Spanish]], the traditional allies of the Tidore Sultans. This murder was soon followed by another one in August 1639, when Gorontalo was killed by a Spanish officer for treacherous collusion with the Ternatans.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1890) ''Bouwstoffen voor de geschiedenis der Nederlanders in den Maleischen Archipel'', Vol. II. 's Gravenhage: Nijhoff, p. 380-3.</ref> Now Tidore was split between two camps; one favoured Gorontalo's son [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Kaicili Golofino]] while another wanted Saidi. The succession dispute lasted into 1640 but was finally resolved in favour of Saidi, who was the Spanish candidate. Ternate's ally, the [[Dutch East India Company]] (VOC) preferred to stay out of this dispute.<ref>W.P. Coolhaas, ed. (1964) ''Generale missiven van Gouverneurs-Generaal en Raden aan Heren XVII der Verenigde Oostindische Compagnie'', Deel II. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 105.</ref>\n\n==Uneasy relationship with the Spanish==\n\nAt his accession Saidi had to promise to fulfill a number of points. He should provide military assistance to the Spanish establishments in Maluku when needed, he was only to sell [[cloves]] to the Spaniards, and he must allow anyone who so desired to become a Catholic. According to Spanish opinions he failed in all these commitments. On the contrary he strove to manage the spice trade in Tidore's own interests and forbade his subjects to sell the cloves to Spanish buyers. Saidi also interfered in the affairs of the [[Sangihe Islands]] north of Maluku, vassals under the [[Spanish Philippines]], where he supported a Muslim rebel with soldiers and Islamic preachers against the Christian ruler of Kalongan. He even had the rebel chief consecrated as ruler in the mosque of Tidore and, in the Spanish interpretation, reserved for himself the role of emperor.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1981) \"The 'Discurso politico del gobierno Maluco' of Fr. Francisco Comb\u00e9s and its historical impact\", ''Philippine Studies'' 29, p. 328.</ref> The precarious situation of the Spanish in Maluku nevertheless forced them to maintain the Tidore alliance, since Saidi was their only potential supporter in the region.\n\n==Continuing struggles against Ternate and the VOC==\n\nThe ongoing war between the [[Spanish Empire]] and the [[Dutch Republic]] was matched by hostilities in Maluku where Spain and Tidore stood against the VOC and Ternate.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1984) ''Documenta Malucensia'', Vol. III. Rome: Jesuit Historical Institute, p. 2-6.</ref> The Dutch actively tried to prevent any attempts to make a separate peace between Ternate and Tidore. The VOC noted that Saidi was a political man who was no great friend of Spain but who strove to secure Tidore's position within the power balance between the Europeans.<ref>W.P. Coolhaas, ed. (1964), p. 589.</ref> Several clashed nevertheless took place during the 1640s. Tidore turned out to be the more successful \"due to its greater carefulness and bravery\"<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895) ''Bouwstoffen voor de geschiedenis der Nederlanders in den Maleischen Archipel'', Vol. III. 's Gravenhage: Nijhoff, p. 443.</ref> Foodstuff was brought to Tidore from its vassals in [[Halmahera]] and even from the [[Raja Ampat|Papuan Islands]], where Tidorese influence had been established by this time. One of Saidi's helpers was the chief Gurabesi whom later traditions associate with the origins of Tidore rule in the Papuan lands.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895), p. 444.</ref> In 1649 a number of battles and mutual raids took place, culminating in a Tidore-Spanish invasion in Ternate where the Dutch were defeated with considerable losses. Before the VOC were able to stage a counter-attack, news of the [[Peace of Westphalia]] reached the East Indies, and hostilities were cancelled.<ref>P.A. Tiele (1895), p. 444-6.</ref>\n\n==Interference in anti-VOC rebellion==\n\nShortly after this, the VOC-backed Sultan of Ternate, [[Mandar Syah]], was opposed by his brothers and part of the Ternatan elite. The Dutch commander Arnold de Vlamingh van Outshoorn suppressed an attempt to replace Mandar Syah, and the Ternatans had to agree on a treaty in 1652 where they were stipulated to extirpate clove trees in their dominions.<ref>Leonard Andaya (1993) ''The world of Maluku''. Honolulu: Hawai'i University Press, p. 167-8.</ref> This would ensure VOC monopoly on the spice trade, but the treaty was insufficient as long as Tidore sold its cloves to other buyers. Since Saidi actively supported the rebels in Ternate without Spanish approval, De Vlamingh van Outshoorn declared war on Tidore, hoping to eliminate the Tidorese clove production. In order not to antagonize the Spanish, [[Tidore Island]] was not attacked; rather, an expedition under Simon Cos was dispatched to worst Tidore's vassals in Halmahera and the Papuan Islands. The expedition was not particularly successful, and in the meantime the Papuan Raja of [[Salawati]] raided in [[Ambon]] on behalf of Sultan Saidi.<ref>P.J.B.C. Robid\u00e9 van der Aa (1879) ''Reizen naar Nederlandsch Nieuw-Guinea''. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 358.[https://archive.org/details/reizennaarneder00crabgoog/page/n400/mode/2up]</ref> However, the efforts of Saidi to take over the Ternatan parts of Halmahera also failed, and the increasingly irritated Spanish finally arrested the Sultan in 1654 for disturbing the peace. He was however soon set free again, and peace with the VOC followed.<ref>A. Haga (1884) ''Nederlandsch Nieuw Guinea en de Papoesche eilanden. Historische bijdrage, 1500-1883''. Batavia: Bruing, p. 67-8.[https://archive.org/details/nederlandschnie01wetegoog/page/n124/mode/2up]</ref> The Spanish claimed that they saved the skins of the Dutch in Maluku by depriving the rebels in Ternate and Ambon of Tidorese support.<ref>Hubert Jacobs (1981), 332-3.</ref>\n\n==Death==\n\nSultan Saidi passed away on 7 January 1657, since long suffering from [[leprocy]]. His demise immediately triggered a succession war. He sired two sons called Weda (alias Mole) and Duko, and a daughter who had been betrothed to Mandar Syah in 1651 though the engagement was broken due to the war.<ref>C.F. van Fraassen (1987) ''Ternate, de Molukken en de Indonesische Archipel''. Leiden: Rijksmuseum te Leiden, Vol. II, p. 20.</ref> Weda was proclaimed Sultan on his father's demise. However, the VOC and Ternate brought forward Kaicili Golofino who had stayed in exile in Ternate since 1640. Golofino soon had the upper hand and was enthroned under the name [[Saifuddin of Tidore|Sultan Saifuddin]].<ref>Coolhaas, W.P., ed. (1968) ''Generale missiven van Gouverneurs-Generaal en Raden aan Heren XVII der Verenigde Oostindische Compagnie'', Deel III. 's-Gravenhage: M. Nijhoff, p. 150.</ref> Under him Tidore finally took the step from a Spanish to a Dutch ally.<ref>Leonard Andaya (1993), p. 170-1.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rulers of Maluku]]\n* [[Spice trade]]\n* [[Tidore Sultanate]]\n* [[Sultanate of Ternate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gorontalo of Tidore|Gorontalo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Sultan of Tidore|years=1640-1657}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Saifuddin of Tidore|Saifuddin]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[Category:People from Maluku Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Kleuske", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saidi_of_Tidore"}
{"title_page": "Testament discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist          = [[Testament (band)|Testament]]\n| Image           = Testament Sweden Rock 2008.jpg\n| Caption         = Testament at Sweden Rock 2008\n| Studio          = 13\n| Live            = 4\n| Compilation     = 5\n| Video           = 3\n| EP              = 2\n| Singles         = 13\n}}\n\nThis is a comprehensive '''[[discography]] of [[Testament (band)|Testament]]''', a [[San Francisco]]-based [[thrash metal]] band, consists of thirteen [[studio album]]s, four [[live albums]], five [[compilation album|compilations]], two [[extended play]]s, thirteen [[single (music)|singles]], and three [[video album]]s. Originally forming in 1983 under the name Legacy they released two [[demo (music)|demo]]s titled Demo 1 and Demo 2 and have since gone on to become one of the most influential thrash metal bands of all time. The band has gone through numerous lineup changes with the only constant member being guitarist [[Eric Peterson (musician)|Eric Peterson]].\n\n==Studio albums==\n{| class =\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"12\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"US\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/testament-mn0000751910/awards|title=Testament - Awards|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br /><ref name=\"AUT\">{{cite web| url=http://www.austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Testament |title=Discographie Testament |language=German |publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=2008-09-03}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:75%\"|[[The Official Finnish Charts|FIN]]<br /><ref name=\"FIN\">{{cite web| url=http://finnishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Testament |title=Discography Testament 