{"title_page": "Episode 8325", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n{{Very long|date=March 2020}}\n{{All plot|date=March 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n\n| title = Episode 8325\n| series = [[Neighbours]]\n| episode = 8325\n| airdate = 23 March 2020\n| writer = [[Jason Herbison]]\n| director = Tony Gardiner ACS\n| guests = * Isla Goulas as [[Aster Conway]]\n| prev = Episode 8324\n| next = Episode 8326\n}}\n\"'''Episode 8325'''\" is the 8,325th episode of the Australian soap opera ''[[Neighbours]]''. It premiered on [[10 Peach]] in Australia and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in the United Kingdom on 23 March 2020. The episode was written by series producer [[Jason Herbison]] and directed by Tony Gardiner ACS. The episode is mainly a two-hander between [[Finn Kelly]] ([[Rob Mills]]) and [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]). It serves as part of the conclusion to Finn's storyline, in which he retains the memories he lost after being pushed off a cliff by Susan, resulting in a deadly revenge during the 35th anniversary week. \n\n==Plot==\n[[Finn Kelly]] ([[Rob Mills]]) returns to [[Ramsay Street]] after killing [[Gary Canning]] ([[Damien Richardson (actor)|Damien Richardson]]), kidnapping [[Aster Conway]] (Isla Goulas), and setting fire to [[Pierce Greyson]]'s ([[Tim Robards]]) island. He lies to [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]) that her niece [[Bea Nilsson]] ([[Bonnie Anderson (singer)|Bonnie Anderson]]) is waiting for them at a log cabin in the [[Snowy Mountains]] while Aster's mother [[Elly Conway]] ([[Jodi Anasta]]) has elected to remain on Pierce's island. Despite the late hour, Susan agrees to go with Finn in her car.\n\nWhile on the way to the cabin, Susan discovers Aster in the backseat of the car and confronts Finn about his true intentions. Finn confesses that he wants to start a new life with her, Aster and his friend [[Harry Sinclair]] ([[Paul Dawber]]). Finn also reveals that his memories of the evil he committed during the first time he lived on Ramsay Street have returned and that he wanted both Bea and Elly out of the way after the former was in the way of a relationship with Elly and the latter refused to come with him. Susan subsequently tells Finn that he is not well, needs help and that the other residents of Ramsay street would understand his situation. Finn manipulates Susan by telling her that she is more like a mother to him than his real mother ever was and that she does not need her husband [[Karl Kennedy]] ([[Alan Fletcher (actor)|Alan Fletcher]]).\n\nAfter arriving at the cabin, Finn sets Aster down to rest and becomes violent and aggressive towards Susan, forcing her to stay with him despite her suspicions. As they lie down to sleep, Finn tells Susan about his dark childhood memories where his mother [[Claudia Watkins]] (Kate Raison) berated him for being mean to his younger brother [[Shaun Watkins]] (Brad Moller), although he was just playing with him. This results in Finn breaking down in tears, and Susan comforts him. Susan later wakes up in the middle of the night, trying to escape the cabin, and picks up a piece of a vase she had accidentally broken earlier, contemplating whether to attack Finn with it. She tells Finn that she thought Harry had returned, and Finn once again becomes aggressive, inadvertently waking up Aster.\n\nThe next morning, Finn wakes up and pretends to have a shower. As he is doing this, Susan picks up her phone and attempts to call emergency services. However, Finn soon catches her in the act and realises that she has been doubting him and does not want to start a new life with him. Enraged, he ties Susan to a chair as she shouts at him to confess to what he has really done to Bea and Elly. Finn eventually reveals that he has pushed Bea down a mineshaft on the island, abandoned Elly there as well and killed Gary with an arrow. He then leaves the cabin to dig a hole to eliminate Susan with the help of a water pipe to soften the earth. Susan then screams for help, while trying to free herself as Finn informs her that no one can hear her, waking up Aster.\n\n==Production==\n===Conception===\nIn December 2019, Mills confirmed that he had left ''[[Neighbours]]'' and that his final scenes would air in early 2020.<ref name=\"FByrne\">{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/fiona-byrne/rob-mills-reveals-key-to-budding-romance/news-story/1549ac590ad5faf4df47f00aa3adaf69|title=Rob Mills and girlfriend Georgie Tunny reveal key to romance|last=Byrne|first=Fiona|date=29 December 2019|work=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=29 December 2019}}{{subscription}}</ref>. It was confirmed in early February 2020 that Finn's departure would tie into  ''[[Neighbours]]''' 35th anniversary celebrations and that three characters would die during the celebrations as a result of a revenge storyline for Finn after his memories returned.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Three deaths, five weddings for Neighbours 35th anniversary |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/02/three-deaths-five-weddings-for-neighbours-35th-anniversary.html |website=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n[[File: Rob Mills.jpg|right|155px|thumb|The episode served as part of the departure storyline for [[Rob Mills]]' character [[Finn Kelly]]]]\n\n==Reception==\nThe original broadcast of \"Episode 8325\" was watched by 149,000 viewers in Australia,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Monday 23 March 2020 |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/monday-23-march-2020.html |publisher=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> which was a small increase from the previous day's episode.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Friday 20 March 2020 |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/friday-20-march-2020.html |publisher=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbours episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 Australian television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Jason Herbison]]\n[[Category:Two-handers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n{{Very long|date=March 2020}}\n{{All plot|date=March 2020}}\n{{Overly detailed|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n\n| title = Episode 8325\n| series = [[Neighbours]]\n| episode = 8325\n| airdate = 23 March 2020\n| writer = [[Jason Herbison]]\n| director = Tony Gardiner ACS\n| guests = * Isla Goulas as [[Aster Conway]]\n| prev = Episode 8324\n| next = Episode 8326\n}}\n\"'''Episode 8325'''\" is the 8,325th episode of the Australian soap opera ''[[Neighbours]]''. It premiered on [[10 Peach]] in Australia and [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] in the United Kingdom on 23 March 2020. The episode was written by series producer [[Jason Herbison]] and directed by Tony Gardiner ACS. The episode is mainly a two-hander between [[Finn Kelly]] ([[Rob Mills]]) and [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]). It serves as part of the conclusion to Finn's storyline, in which he retains the memories he lost after being pushed off a cliff by Susan, resulting in a deadly revenge during the 35th anniversary week. \n\n==Plot==\n[[Finn Kelly]] ([[Rob Mills]]) returns to [[Ramsay Street]] after killing [[Gary Canning]] ([[Damien Richardson (actor)|Damien Richardson]]), kidnapping [[Aster Conway]] (Isla Goulas), and setting fire to [[Pierce Greyson]]'s ([[Tim Robards]]) island. He lies to [[Susan Kennedy]] ([[Jackie Woodburne]]) that her niece [[Bea Nilsson]] ([[Bonnie Anderson (singer)|Bonnie Anderson]]) is waiting for them at a log cabin in the [[Snowy Mountains]] while Aster's mother [[Elly Conway]] ([[Jodi Anasta]]) has elected to remain on Pierce's island. Despite the late hour, Susan agrees to go with Finn in her car.\n\nWhile on the way to the cabin, Susan discovers Aster in the backseat of the car and confronts Finn about his true intentions. Finn confesses that he wants to start a new life with her, Aster and his friend [[Harry Sinclair]] ([[Paul Dawber]]). Finn also reveals that his memories of the evil he committed during the first time he lived on Ramsay Street have returned and that he wanted both Bea and Elly out of the way after the former was in the way of a relationship with Elly and the latter refused to come with him. Susan subsequently tells Finn that he is not well, needs help and that the other residents of Ramsay street would understand his situation. Finn manipulates Susan by telling her that she is more like a mother to him than his real mother ever was and that she does not need her husband [[Karl Kennedy]] ([[Alan Fletcher]]).\n\nAfter arriving at the cabin, Finn sets Aster down to rest and becomes violent and aggressive towards Susan, forcing her to stay with him despite her suspicions. As they lie down to sleep, Finn tells Susan about his dark childhood memories where his mother [[Claudia Watkins]] (Kate Raison) berated him for being mean to his younger brother [[Shaun Watkins]] (Brad Moller), although he was just playing with him. This results in Finn breaking down in tears, and Susan comforts him. Susan later wakes up in the middle of the night, trying to escape the cabin, and picks up a piece of a vase she had accidentally broken earlier, contemplating whether to attack Finn with it. She tells Finn that she thought Harry had returned, and Finn once again becomes aggressive, inadvertently waking up Aster.\n\nThe next morning, Finn wakes up and pretends to have a shower. As he is doing this, Susan picks up her phone and attempts to call emergency services. However, Finn soon catches her in the act and realises that she has been doubting him and does not want to start a new life with him. Enraged, he ties Susan to a chair as she shouts at him to confess to what he has really done to Bea and Elly. Finn eventually reveals that he has pushed Bea down a mineshaft on the island, abandoned Elly there as well and killed Gary with an arrow. He then leaves the cabin to dig a hole to eliminate Susan with the help of a water pipe to soften the earth. Susan then screams for help, while trying to free herself as Finn informs her that no one can hear her, waking up Aster.\n\n==Production==\n===Conception===\nIn December 2019, Mills confirmed that he had left ''[[Neighbours]]'' and that his final scenes would air in early 2020.<ref name=\"FByrne\">{{cite news|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/fiona-byrne/rob-mills-reveals-key-to-budding-romance/news-story/1549ac590ad5faf4df47f00aa3adaf69|title=Rob Mills and girlfriend Georgie Tunny reveal key to romance|last=Byrne|first=Fiona|date=29 December 2019|work=[[Herald Sun]]|accessdate=29 December 2019}}{{subscription}}</ref>. It was confirmed in early February 2020 that Finn's departure would tie into  ''[[Neighbours]]''' 35th anniversary celebrations and that three characters would die during the celebrations as a result of a revenge storyline for Finn after his memories returned.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Three deaths, five weddings for Neighbours 35th anniversary |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/02/three-deaths-five-weddings-for-neighbours-35th-anniversary.html |website=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n[[File: Rob Mills.jpg|right|155px|thumb|The episode served as part of the departure storyline for [[Rob Mills]]' character [[Finn Kelly]]]]\n\n==Reception==\nThe original broadcast of \"Episode 8325\" was watched by 149,000 viewers in Australia,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Monday 23 March 2020 |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/monday-23-march-2020.html |publisher=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> which was a small increase from the previous day's episode.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Knox |first1=David |title=Friday 20 March 2020 |url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/friday-20-march-2020.html |publisher=TV Tonight |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbours episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 Australian television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Jason Herbison]]\n[[Category:Two-handers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAlan Fletcher(link changed toAlan Fletcher (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Episode_8325"}
{"title_page": "Celebrity Name Game (Australian game show)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Australian game show}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Celebrity Name Game\n| image                = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Game show\n| creator              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Debmar-Mercury]]\n* [[FremantleMedia North America]]\n}}\n| based_on             = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Celebrity Name Game (American game show)|Celebrity Name Game]]''\n* ''Identity Crisis''\n}}\n| developer            = \n| writer               = [[Henry Stone (comedian)|Henry Stone]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = Peter Ots\n| creative_director    = Jennifer Collins\n| presenter            = [[Grant Denyer]]\n| theme_music_composer = Tim Mosher & Stoker\n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = Australia\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons<!--Both terms are correct-->          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 144 <!-- as of 16 March 2020 -->\n| list_episodes        = List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Caroline Spencer\n* Dan Sheldon\n* Maria Michael\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Catherine Bradbury\n* Paul Millgate\n}}\n| location             = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| editor               = <!-- Film editors -->\n| camera               = Multi-camera\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[Fremantle Australia|FremantleMedia Australia]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n| network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Network 10]]\n* [[10 Bold]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n* 576i\n* [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n}}\n| audio_format         = Stereo\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2019|05|13|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = https://10play.com.au/celebrity-name-game\n| production_website   = https://www.fremantleaustralia.com/shows#Celebrity_Name_Game\n}}\n'''''Celebrity Name Game''''' is an Australian game show based on the [[Celebrity Name Game (American game show)|American show of the same name]] and the board game ''Identity Crisis'' (created by Laura Robinson and Richard Gerrits) hosted by [[Grant Denyer]] and first premiered on [[Network 10]] on 13 May 2019.<ref name=CelebNameGameLaunch>{{cite web|title=Airdate: Celebrity Name Game|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/04/airdate-celebrity-name-game.html|work=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|accessdate=26 April 2019|date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=CelebrityMediaRelease>{{cite media release|title=Put Your Game Face On! |url=https://images.tenplay.com.au/~/media/Corporate%20Site%20Media/Files/Media%20Releases/2019/190426%20Put%20Your%20Game%20Face%20On%20Celebrity%20Name%20Game%20starts%20Monday%2013%20May.pdf|first=Laura|last=Ianni|work=Network 10 |accessdate=26 April 2019|date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Summer of 2019-20, ''Celebrity Name Game'' moved to [[10 Bold]] as a result of an extended 90 minute ''[[10 News First]]'' bulletin over the Summer.<ref name=\"10BOLD Summer\">{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/11/10-news-first-to-trial-90-minute-bulletins.html|title=10 News First to trial 90 Minute Bulletins|publisher=TV Tonight|date=30 November 2019|website=TV Tonight|access-date=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n===Main game===\nThe game involves two teams, each consisting of two contestants who are related or know each other. They are joined by two guest celebrities who assist the teams for all but the third segment of the show, attempting to identify the names of popular culture subjects like celebrities, fictional characters, place names, or film and television titles.\n\nIn the first two rounds, each team is assigned one of the celebrities, who then will switch teams for the second round. Each of the three-member teams are presented with a category containing ten names. One person will give clues, trying to get the other two to guess the names. Successful guesses earn money. An illegal clue (saying the name or part of the name, spelling the name, or rhyming the name) voids that name. Each turn lasts for 45 seconds. In the first round, one team is chosen to play first, and chooses one of two categories presented, leaving the second team to play the remaining category. In the second round, the second team plays first and chooses the first category.\n\nIn round one, the celebrity gives the clues while turning back and forth to alternately face each contestant, and each correct answer is worth $100, up to $1,000 total. In round two, one of the two contestants gives clues while alternately facing either the remaining partner or the assigned celebrity, and each answer is worth $200, up to $2,000 total.\n\nIn the third round, the contestants go head to head while Denyer gives the clues to names under a specific category. The contestants buzz in to make a guess. If neither contestant buzzes in after a while, Denyer can start giving out clues that are normally illegal, all the way up to simply saying the name. A right answer earns money for the team that answered, but a wrong answer grants the money to the opponent. The first answer is worth $100 and each successive answer increases in value by $100. Winnings in this round are added to the money accumulated in the first two rounds, and whichever team reaches $3,000 or more first is the winner, keeps the cash, and goes on to the bonus round to play for the prize of $10,000. If no team reaches $3,000 before time is called, the team in the lead at the end of the round wins the game. If the game ends in a tie, one final name is given; a team who buzzes in with a correct answer wins the game, but a wrong answer results in an automatic loss.\n\n===Bonus round===\nIn the bonus round, there is no particular category. The names of people, characters, places, shows or things are hidden behind ten numbered squares. The contestants take turns giving the clues to both celebrities. One contestant is placed in a soundproof booth while the other gives clues. The current giver starts describing when a name or picture is exposed. If the celebrity receivers get it right, the name stays revealed. Passing on a name re-conceals it. This round lasts for a total of 75 seconds, the first contestant has 45 seconds, and the second has 30 seconds. If the first clue giver provides an illegal clue to a name, that name is replaced by a different one for the second clue giver. Any illegal clue by the second clue giver, however, ends the round immediately. Getting all ten increases the team's total winnings to $10,000. If the first contestant correctly guesses all ten names within 45 seconds or less, the second portion of the round is not played. Otherwise, the team takes home only the amount they had earned by the end of Round 3.\n\n==Production and broadcast==\n''Celebrity Name Game'' airs in a 6:00 pm timeslot and is broadcast five nights a week from Mondays to Fridays. The show is filmed at [[Network 10]]'s [[TEN (TV Station)#Studio facilities|studios]] in Pyrmont, Sydney as of 2019.<ref name=CelebNameGameLaunch/><ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Name Game Audience Registration|url=https://fmau.etribez.com/ag/fmau/cng/welcome.html|work=eTribez|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\nA board game featuring Denyer on the cover was released by Imagination Gaming<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onlinetoys.com.au/celebrity-name-game-board-game.html|title=Celebrity Name Game \u2014 Board Game}}</ref> in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmart.com.au/product/celebrity-name-game/2624801|title=Celebrity Name Game Board Game \u2014 Kmart|accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{main|List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes}}\n\n{{:List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes}}\n\n===Hosts===\n* [[Grant Denyer]]\n* [[Rove McManus]] (10 episodes)\n\n===Celebrities===\n* [[Tommy Little (comedian)|Tommy Little]]\n* [[Lisa Wilkinson]]\n* [[Beau Ryan]]\n* [[Sam Simmons (comedian)|Sam Simmons]]\n* Yvie Jones\n* Angie Kent\n* [[Lawrence Leung]]\n* [[Scott Tweedie]]\n* [[Sharna Burgess]]\n* [[Tristan MacManus]]\n* [[Courtney Act]]\n* [[Tahir Bilgi\u00e7]]\n* [[Susie Youssef]]\n* [[Jane Hall (actress)|Jane Hall]]\n* [[Ed Kavalee]]\n* Ash London\n* [[Olympia Valance]]\n* [[Merrick Watts]]\n* [[Peter Rowsthorn (actor)|Peter Rowsthorn]]\n* Matty Johnson\n* [[Tom Ballard]]\n* [[Lucy Durack]]\n* [[Gina Liano]]\n* [[Brendan Jones (radio personality)|Brendan Jones]]\n* [[Casey Donovan (singer)|Casey Donovan]]\n* [[Denise Drysdale]]\n* [[Jessica Rowe]]\n* [[Johnny Ruffo]]\n* [[Rhonda Burchmore]]\n* [[Jay Pharoah]]\n* [[Sarah Harris (journalist)|Sarah Harris]]\n* [[Angela Bishop]]\n* [[Annie Maynard]]\n* [[Stephanie Rice]]\n* [[The Umbilical Brothers]]\n* Tim Blackwell\n* [[Michelle Bridges]]\n* [[Nazeem Hussain]]\n* [[Nikki Osborne]]\n* [[Paul Fenech]]\n* Harley Breen\n* [[Cal Wilson]]\n* [[Natarsha Belling]]\n* [[Merv Hughes]]\n* [[Amos Gill]]\n* [[Alan Fletcher (actor)|Alan Fletcher]]\n* [[Ryan Moloney]]\n* Hans\n* [[Dave Thornton]]\n* Nath Valvo\n* [[Lisa Curry]]\n* [[Steve Willis]]\n* [[Gyton Grantley]]\n* Tanya Hennessy\n* [[Gary Mehigan]]\n* Matt Sinclair\n* [[Julie Goodwin]]\n* [[Damian Walshe-Howling]]\n* Ivan Aristeguieta\n* [[George Calombaris]]\n* Anna Polyviou\n* [[Rove McManus]]\n* [[Peter Helliar]]\n* Georgie Carroll\n* [[Melody Thornton]]\n* Justin Lacko\n* [[Natalie Bassingthwaighte]]\n* Will McMahon\n* Woody Whitelaw\n* [[John Edward]]\n* [[Osher G\u00fcnsberg]]\n* [[Dave O'Neil]]\n* [[Joe Hildebrand]]\n* [[Anthony Callea]]\n* [[James Mathison]]\n* [[Vicky Pattison]]\n* [[Shannon Noll]]\n* [[Bernard Curry]]\n* Ebony Vagulans\n* [[Tim Campbell (actor)|Tim Campbell]]\n* [[Veronica Milsom]]\n* [[Lewis Hobba]]\n* [[Celia Pacquola]]\n* [[Steven Bradbury]]\n* Georgia Love\n* Lee Elliot\n* [[Dylan Lewis]]\n* [[Kent Small]]\n* [[Ash Pollard]]\n* [[Steen Raskopoulos]]\n* Matt Farrelly\n* [[Janine Allis]]\n* [[Andrew Ettingshausen]]\n* [[Bonnie Lythgoe]]\n* Alex Jae\n* Alex Lee\n* [[Ian \"Dicko\" Dickson]]\n* [[Mel Buttle]]\n* [[Bonnie Anderson]]\n* [[Matt Burke]]\n* [[David Campese]]\n* [[Jimeoin]]\n* [[Liz Ellis]]\n* [[Catherine Cox]]\n* [[Erika Heynatz]]\n* [[Nicola Parry]]\n* [[Heidi Arena]]\n* [[Roxy Jacenko]]\n* [[Wippa]]\n* [[Richard Reid (entertainment reporter)|Richard Reid]]\n* [[Stacey Thomson]]\n* [[John Foreman (musician)|John Foreman]]\n* [[Christie Whelan Browne]]\n* [[Jett Kenny]]\n* [[Dave Hughes]]\n* [[Charlie Pickering]]\n* [[Dannii Minogue]]\n* [[Luke McGregor]]\n* [[Chris Brown (veterinarian)|Chris Brown]]\n* [[Gretel Killeen]]\n* Kate McCartney\n* [[Kate McLennan]]\n* [[Rob Mills]]\n* [[Melissa Tkautz]]\n* Anthony \"Harries\" Carrol\n* Bruce \"Hoppo\" Hopkins\n* Patrick Abboud\n* [[Lehmo]]\n* Nikki Britton\n* [[Scott McLaughlin (racing driver)|Scott McLaughlin]]\n* [[David Reynolds (racing driver)|David Reynolds]]\n*\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://10play.com.au/celebrity-name-game}}\n*[https://www.fremantleaustralia.com/shows#Celebrity_Name_Game Production website]\n\n{{Network Ten programming}}\n\n[[Category:Network 10 shows]]\n[[Category:2019 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian game shows]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremantle (company)]]\n[[Category:Australian television series based on American television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Australian game show}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Celebrity Name Game\n| image                = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = Game show\n| creator              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Debmar-Mercury]]\n* [[FremantleMedia North America]]\n}}\n| based_on             = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Celebrity Name Game (American game show)|Celebrity Name Game]]''\n* ''Identity Crisis''\n}}\n| developer            = \n| writer               = [[Henry Stone (comedian)|Henry Stone]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = Peter Ots\n| creative_director    = Jennifer Collins\n| presenter            = [[Grant Denyer]]\n| theme_music_composer = Tim Mosher & Stoker\n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = Australia\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons<!--Both terms are correct-->          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 144 <!-- as of 16 March 2020 -->\n| list_episodes        = List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Caroline Spencer\n* Dan Sheldon\n* Maria Michael\n}}\n| producer             = {{Plainlist|\n* Catherine Bradbury\n* Paul Millgate\n}}\n| location             = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]]\n| editor               = <!-- Film editors -->\n| camera               = Multi-camera\n| runtime              = 30 minutes\n| company              = [[Fremantle Australia|FremantleMedia Australia]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n| network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Network 10]]\n* [[10 Bold]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n* 576i\n* [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n}}\n| audio_format         = Stereo\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2019|05|13|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = present\n| website              = https://10play.com.au/celebrity-name-game\n| production_website   = https://www.fremantleaustralia.com/shows#Celebrity_Name_Game\n}}\n'''''Celebrity Name Game''''' is an Australian game show based on the [[Celebrity Name Game (American game show)|American show of the same name]] and the board game ''Identity Crisis'' (created by Laura Robinson and Richard Gerrits) hosted by [[Grant Denyer]] and first premiered on [[Network 10]] on 13 May 2019.<ref name=CelebNameGameLaunch>{{cite web|title=Airdate: Celebrity Name Game|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/04/airdate-celebrity-name-game.html|work=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|accessdate=26 April 2019|date=26 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=CelebrityMediaRelease>{{cite media release|title=Put Your Game Face On! |url=https://images.tenplay.com.au/~/media/Corporate%20Site%20Media/Files/Media%20Releases/2019/190426%20Put%20Your%20Game%20Face%20On%20Celebrity%20Name%20Game%20starts%20Monday%2013%20May.pdf|first=Laura|last=Ianni|work=Network 10 |accessdate=26 April 2019|date=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Summer of 2019-20, ''Celebrity Name Game'' moved to [[10 Bold]] as a result of an extended 90 minute ''[[10 News First]]'' bulletin over the Summer.<ref name=\"10BOLD Summer\">{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/11/10-news-first-to-trial-90-minute-bulletins.html|title=10 News First to trial 90 Minute Bulletins|publisher=TV Tonight|date=30 November 2019|website=TV Tonight|access-date=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n===Main game===\nThe game involves two teams, each consisting of two contestants who are related or know each other. They are joined by two guest celebrities who assist the teams for all but the third segment of the show, attempting to identify the names of popular culture subjects like celebrities, fictional characters, place names, or film and television titles.\n\nIn the first two rounds, each team is assigned one of the celebrities, who then will switch teams for the second round. Each of the three-member teams are presented with a category containing ten names. One person will give clues, trying to get the other two to guess the names. Successful guesses earn money. An illegal clue (saying the name or part of the name, spelling the name, or rhyming the name) voids that name. Each turn lasts for 45 seconds. In the first round, one team is chosen to play first, and chooses one of two categories presented, leaving the second team to play the remaining category. In the second round, the second team plays first and chooses the first category.\n\nIn round one, the celebrity gives the clues while turning back and forth to alternately face each contestant, and each correct answer is worth $100, up to $1,000 total. In round two, one of the two contestants gives clues while alternately facing either the remaining partner or the assigned celebrity, and each answer is worth $200, up to $2,000 total.\n\nIn the third round, the contestants go head to head while Denyer gives the clues to names under a specific category. The contestants buzz in to make a guess. If neither contestant buzzes in after a while, Denyer can start giving out clues that are normally illegal, all the way up to simply saying the name. A right answer earns money for the team that answered, but a wrong answer grants the money to the opponent. The first answer is worth $100 and each successive answer increases in value by $100. Winnings in this round are added to the money accumulated in the first two rounds, and whichever team reaches $3,000 or more first is the winner, keeps the cash, and goes on to the bonus round to play for the prize of $10,000. If no team reaches $3,000 before time is called, the team in the lead at the end of the round wins the game. If the game ends in a tie, one final name is given; a team who buzzes in with a correct answer wins the game, but a wrong answer results in an automatic loss.\n\n===Bonus round===\nIn the bonus round, there is no particular category. The names of people, characters, places, shows or things are hidden behind ten numbered squares. The contestants take turns giving the clues to both celebrities. One contestant is placed in a soundproof booth while the other gives clues. The current giver starts describing when a name or picture is exposed. If the celebrity receivers get it right, the name stays revealed. Passing on a name re-conceals it. This round lasts for a total of 75 seconds, the first contestant has 45 seconds, and the second has 30 seconds. If the first clue giver provides an illegal clue to a name, that name is replaced by a different one for the second clue giver. Any illegal clue by the second clue giver, however, ends the round immediately. Getting all ten increases the team's total winnings to $10,000. If the first contestant correctly guesses all ten names within 45 seconds or less, the second portion of the round is not played. Otherwise, the team takes home only the amount they had earned by the end of Round 3.\n\n==Production and broadcast==\n''Celebrity Name Game'' airs in a 6:00 pm timeslot and is broadcast five nights a week from Mondays to Fridays. The show is filmed at [[Network 10]]'s [[TEN (TV Station)#Studio facilities|studios]] in Pyrmont, Sydney as of 2019.<ref name=CelebNameGameLaunch/><ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Name Game Audience Registration|url=https://fmau.etribez.com/ag/fmau/cng/welcome.html|work=eTribez|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandise==\nA board game featuring Denyer on the cover was released by Imagination Gaming<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onlinetoys.com.au/celebrity-name-game-board-game.html|title=Celebrity Name Game \u2014 Board Game}}</ref> in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kmart.com.au/product/celebrity-name-game/2624801|title=Celebrity Name Game Board Game \u2014 Kmart|accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{{main|List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes}}\n\n{{:List of Celebrity Name Game Australia episodes}}\n\n===Hosts===\n* [[Grant Denyer]]\n* [[Rove McManus]] (10 episodes)\n\n===Celebrities===\n* [[Tommy Little (comedian)|Tommy Little]]\n* [[Lisa Wilkinson]]\n* [[Beau Ryan]]\n* [[